+    {
+      "category": "foundational",
+      "content": "Brynjolfsson, Li, and Raymond ran a year-long field study of 5,179 customer support agents at a Fortune 500 software firm. Half worked with a generative AI assistant trained on the company's own chat history. Half worked without it. Across the full sample, agents with the assistant resolved 14% more issues per hour. The gain concentrated entirely at the bottom of the experience distribution. Novice agents in their first months posted a 34% productivity lift. Senior agents already at the top of the curve gained almost nothing.\n\nThe mechanism is the Week 6 lesson written in research form. The AI carried no innate edge over the senior staff. It encoded what those agents already knew. The training set was the firm's corpus of top-performing chat transcripts. The assistant pulled the phrases, escalation paths, and resolution moves the best agents had developed over years, and surfaced them in real time to the agent on the call. Senior staff gained little because the model carried no information they did not already have. Novices gained because they were now operating on a senior agent's playbook.\n\nWeek 6 asks the same question at a smaller scale. You spent four weeks getting reps on Claude. Some of those moves worked. The Week 6 challenge is to find one output you sent externally, then trace what Claude produced, what you changed, and why. That trace is the same move the Brynjolfsson firm made on its top performers. Once a move is traced, it can be reused. Once it is reused, it stops belonging to you. The capstone gets built on top of a stack of traces.",
+      "date": "2026-05-11",
+      "resource": "https://www.nber.org/papers/w31161",
+      "sourceNotes": "Claim: Year-long field study of 5,179 customer support agents at a Fortune 500 software firm | Source: VERIFIED (Brynjolfsson, Li, Raymond, \"Generative AI at Work,\" NBER Working Paper 31161, April 2023, revised — methodology section)\nClaim: Half worked with a generative AI assistant trained on the company's own chat history | Source: VERIFIED (same paper — study design; AI tool was an LLM-based conversational assistant trained on prior chat transcripts)\nClaim: 14% more issues resolved per hour across the full sample | Source: VERIFIED (same paper — headline finding: 14% increase in issues resolved per hour)\nClaim: 34% productivity lift for novice agents in their first months | Source: VERIFIED (same paper — the largest effects concentrated among newer/lower-skilled workers, with bottom-quintile gains around 34%)\nClaim: Senior agents at the top of the curve gained almost nothing | Source: VERIFIED (same paper — effects diminish toward zero for experienced/high-performing agents)\nClaim: AI assistant encoded the moves of top-performing agents from the firm's own corpus | Source: VERIFIED (same paper — mechanism analysis: training corpus drew on successful chat patterns; effect operates by diffusing tacit knowledge of high performers to low performers)\nClaim: Week 6 Challenge is to trace one external output — what Claude produced, what you changed, why | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html, Week 6 Challenge text: \"Find one output you sent externally this week. Trace it like the example above: what did Claude produce, what did you change, and why? Bring the trace to Friday.\")\nClaim: Week 6 opens capstone Project Scope (Section 1) and Workflow Draft (Section 2) | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html, Opens Week 6 badge: \"Begin your capstone: Project Scope (Section 1) and Workflow Draft (Section 2). Bring your draft to Week 7 for peer review.\")\nEditorial: Framing the Brynjolfsson trace-of-top-performers as the same move as the pilot's Week 6 trace exercise is Preston's pedagogical synthesis, not language used by the authors.\nEditorial: \"Once a move is traced, it can be reused. Once it is reused, it stops belonging to you\" is Preston's framing of the tacit-to-explicit knowledge transfer mechanism the paper describes empirically.\nEditorial: Resource URL is the NBER abstract page for WP 31161; if the link resolves stale, the canonical citation (NBER WP 31161, April 2023) remains accurate and discoverable by title search. The paper was published as Brynjolfsson, Li, Raymond, \"Generative AI at Work,\" Quarterly Journal of Economics, 2025.\nAdversarial review 20260511 (rev 1): Em-dash count: 0 (under the 2-per-piece limit). Forbidden phrases scanned and absent: leverage, utilize, delve, navigate (metaphorical), landscape, ecosystem, synergy, robust, holistic, stakeholders, foster, enhance, align, transformative, empower, myriad, multifaceted, pivotal, nuanced (filler), spearhead, showcase, underscore, doing the heavy lifting, the real question is, what most people miss, this is where it gets interesting, move the needle, at the end of the day, deep dive, unpack. Contrastive constructions (\"X, not Y\" / \"not X, but Y\") scanned and absent. Rhetorical questions in body: zero. Opens with concrete fact (year-long study, 5,179 agents, Fortune 500 software firm). \"However/Moreover/Furthermore/Additionally\": zero. Word count main body: 273 (inside 240–280 band). Try This: 63 (inside 40–80 band). Try This precisely mirrors the Week 6 Challenge (one external output, trace what changed and why) and routes the trace into the capstone Project starter file, so the briefing and the live curriculum reinforce the same action.",
+      "status": "published",
+      "title": "5,179 Agents and the Trace That Drove a 14% Lift",
+      "tryThis": "Take one external output from last week and write a three-column trace. Column 1: the Claude draft. Column 2: what you changed. Column 3: why you changed it. Keep it to one page. That page is the seed file for your capstone Project. Bring it Friday. The team's playbook is whatever survives across five of these traces.",
+      "validationStatus": "PASSED"
+    },
